BULLETIN - EAS ACTIVATION REQUESTED   
FLASH FLOOD WARNING   
NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE JACKSON KY   
733 AM EDT TUE APR 12 2011   
   
THE NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE IN JACKSON KY HAS ISSUED A   
   
* FLASH FLOOD WARNING FOR...   
  EAST CENTRAL BATH COUNTY IN EAST CENTRAL KENTUCKY...   
  EXTREME NORTH CENTRAL MORGAN COUNTY IN SOUTHEAST KENTUCKY...   
  ROWAN COUNTY IN EAST CENTRAL KENTUCKY...   
  SOUTHEASTERN FLEMING COUNTY IN EAST CENTRAL KENTUCKY...   
  WEST CENTRAL ELLIOTT COUNTY IN EAST CENTRAL KENTUCKY...   
   
* UNTIL 130 PM EDT   
   
* AT 730 AM EDT...NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE DOPPLER RADAR INDICATED   
  SLOW MOVING THUNDERSTORMS WITH VERY HEAVY RAINFALL ACROSS THE         
  WARNED AREA. RADAR ESTIMATES THAT AN INCH TO AN INCH AND A    
  HALF HAS FALLEN OVER PARTS OF THE WARNED AREA JUST TO THE   
  SOUTHEAST OF THE CITY OF MOREHEAD. ADDITIONAL RAINFALL OF    
  UP TO AN INCH SHOULD FALL IN THE NEXT HOUR OR SO ACROSS   
  SECTIONS OF THE WARNING TO THE NORTH OF INTERSTATE 64.    
   
* RUNOFF FROM THIS EXCESSIVE RAINFALL WILL CAUSE FLASH FLOODING TO   
  OCCUR. SOME LOCATIONS THAT WILL EXPERIENCE FLOODING INCLUDE...   
  MOREHEAD...BLAIRS MILLS...BLUESTONE...BRANDY...CHRISTY...   
  CLEARFIELD...CRANEY...CRANSTON...CRIX...ELLIOTTVILLE...FANNIN   
  VALLEY...FARLEY...FARMERS...FREESTONE...GATES...HALDEMAN...HAMM...   
  HAYS CROSSING...HILDA...LICK FORK...LYTTEN...MINOR...MUNSON...   
  PELFREY...RAMEY...RINGOS MILLS...RODBURN...SHARKEY...TRIPLETT AND   
  VALE.   
   
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...   
   
EXCESSIVE RUNOFF FROM HEAVY RAINFALL WILL CAUSE FLOODING OF SMALL   
CREEKS AND STREAMS...COUNTRY ROADS...AS WELL AS FARMLAND ALONG THE   
BANKS OF CREEKS AND STREAMS.   
   
xx   
   
LAT...LON 3834 8336 3834 8334 3832 8333 3823 8330   
   
$$   
   
PELTON

DAY 1 CONVECTIVE OUTLOOK     
NWS STORM PREDICTION CENTER NORMAN OK   
1052 AM CDT TUE APR 12 2011   
   
VALID 121630Z - 131200Z   
   
...THERE IS A SLGT RISK OF SVR TSTMS OVER PORTIONS OF EASTERN   
VA/NC...   
   
...MID ATLANTIC COAST...   
IMPRESSIVE UPPER LOW NOW CROSSING THE SRN APPALACHIANS WILL MOVE   
SLOWLY ENEWD TO AROUND DELMARVA AREA BY 12Z WED.  SLY FLOW IN   
ADVANCE OF THE LOW HAS SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASED THE MOISTURE NWD THRU   
ERN NC INTO SERN VA THIS AM. HOWEVER RELATIVELY POOR LAPSE RATES AND   
CAPPING ON THE MORNING SOUNDINGS SUGGEST INSTABILITY WILL BE LIMITED   
UNTIL THE MID LEVEL COOLING WHEN UPPER SYSTEM APPROACHES THIS   
AFTERNOON.   
   
WHILE VEERING WINDS WILL SLOWLY SHUNT DEEPER MOISTURE OFFSHORE...   
COOLING MID LEVEL TEMPERATURES AND LARGE SCALE ASCENT WILL SLOWLY   
STEEPEN LAPSE RATES AND EVENTUALLY RESULT IN A FAVORABLE   
THERMODYNAMIC PROFILE FOR HAIL IN THE STRONGER STORMS.  70+ KT MID   
LEVEL WINDS WILL ALSO COMBINE WITH RATHER STEEP LOW LEVEL LAPSE   
RATES TO PROMOTE A RISK OF LOCALLY DAMAGING WINDS.  THE SEVERE   
THREAT SHOULD BE RELATIVELY CONFINED IN SPACE AND TIME...WITH STORMS   
MOVING OFFSHORE BY EARLY EVENING.   
   
ADDITIONALLY THERE WILL BE SOME THREAT OF HAIL IN THE COLD CORE   
MOVING WITH THE UPPER LOW ACROSS THE MOUNTAINS OF VA/WV.   
   
..HALES/COHEN.. 04/12/2011

properties.name: SPC-Day2 Discussion
properties.description:
ACUS02 KWNS 121613   
SWODY2   
SPC AC 121612   
   
DAY 2 CONVECTIVE OUTLOOK     
NWS STORM PREDICTION CENTER NORMAN OK   
1112 AM CDT TUE APR 12 2011   
   
VALID 131200Z - 141200Z   
   
...NO SVR TSTM AREAS FORECAST...   
   
...SYNOPSIS...   
   
A RATHER BENIGN PATTERN HAS ESTABLISHED ITSELF REGARDING THE   
PROSPECT FOR ORGANIZED SEVERE WEATHER DURING THE DAY2 PERIOD.  EVEN   
SO THERE WILL BE POCKETS OF SUFFICIENT MOISTURE/INSTABILITY WHERE   
ISOLATED-SCT LIGHTNING MAY BE NOTED.  IN THE EAST...A FEW ELEVATED   
THUNDERSTORMS MAY BE ONGOING AT THE BEGINNING OF THE PERIOD OVER   
SERN MA WITHIN STRONG WARM ADVECTION ZONE.  THIS ACTIVITY WILL SHIFT   
OFFSHORE DURING THE LATTER HALF OF THE PERIOD WITH STRONGER FORCING.   
UPSTREAM...LEE CYCLOGENESIS WILL DEVELOP OVER WRN KS THEN DRIFT   
SOUTH INTO THE TX PANHANDLE BY AFTERNOON.  A NEWD EXTENSION OF THIS   
FEATURE IN THE FORM OF A SFC FRONT WILL BE DRAPED FROM THE ERN OK   
PANHANDLE INTO CNTRL IA.  STRONG HEATING ALONG THIS BOUNDARY IN   
CONJUNCTION WITH ROUGHLY .75 PWAT MAY PROVE ADEQUATE FOR A FEW   
THUNDERSTORMS BY LATE AFTERNOON.  LOW LEVEL WARM ADVECTION ALONG   
THIS ZONE AFTER DARK MAY ALLOW THIS ACTIVITY TO LINGER INTO THE   
OVERNIGHT HOURS.   
   
SCATTERED THUNDERSTORMS WILL ONCE AGAIN DEVELOP ACROSS PORTIONS OF   
THE INTERIOR WEST...ESPECIALLY ACROSS PORTIONS OF ID INTO NRN   
UT/NWRN CO.  STRONG FORCING WITHIN UPPER DIFFLUENT ZONE WILL   
ENCOURAGE CONVECTIVE DEVELOPMENT...ESPECIALLY OVER THE HIGHER   
TERRAIN.  ALTHOUGH MOISTURE IS EXPECTED TO REMAIN SOMEWHAT   
MARGINAL...VERY COLD MID LEVEL TEMPERATURES WILL LEAD TO AMPLE   
INSTABILITY.  IN FACT...FORECAST SOUNDINGS SUGGEST 500-900 J/KG   
SBCAPE IS POSSIBLE ACROSS PARTS OF NRN UT BY LATE AFTERNOON.    
THUNDERSTORMS SHOULD EASILY DEVELOP ACROSS THIS REGION IF THESE   
CONDITIONS MATERIALIZE.   
   
A FEW THUNDERSTORMS MAY ALSO BE NOTED ALONG THE PACIFIC NW COAST   
WITHIN ONSHORE FLOW BENEATH COOLING THICKNESS.   
   
..DARROW.. 04/12/2011
